"# Chapter 6: Noise & Texture

A sine wave is pure—too pure. Real instruments breathe, rattle, scrape. A bow chatters against a string. A cymbal hisses. Wind tumbles through a pipe. These aren't mistakes; they're texture, and they come from **noise**—sound with no pitch, just energy scattered across every frequency at once.

This chapter drills noise: white and pink, shaped by filters and envelopes, layered with tones to turn beeps into instruments and silence into weather. By the end you'll build a hi-hat from scratch, layer breath into a flute, and hear why a snare drum without noise is just a dull thud.

---

## White Noise — Every Frequency at Once

White noise is the hiss of an untuned radio, the static between stations. Every frequency plays at equal energy, all the time. It has no pitch because it has *every* pitch.

```scheme
;; Pure white noise for one second
(noise 'white 1.0)
```

That's the raw material. Alone it sounds like static, but shaped—filtered, enveloped—it becomes wind, breath, cymbals, ocean.

---

## Pink Noise — Weighted Toward the Low End

White noise can feel harsh because high frequencies dominate our perception. **Pink noise** rolls off the highs—each octave carries equal energy, so it sounds warmer, more natural. Rain on a roof. Distant waterfalls.

```scheme
;; Pink noise for two seconds — warmer, less hissy
(noise 'pink 2.0)
```

*[needs: noise-pink]*  
<!-- BUILD: noise-pink — spectral shaping, 1/f or per-octave rolloff -->

[VISUAL: Two waveform + spectrum pairs side-by-side — white noise flat across all frequencies, pink noise sloping down at higher frequencies]

---

## Filtering Noise — Sculpting the Hiss

Chapter 4 gave us filters. Apply a **lowpass** to white noise and you get wind. A **highpass** leaves only the shimmer. A **bandpass** isolates a slice—narrow it with resonance (high Q) and the noise almost has a pitch.

```scheme
;; Lowpass white noise → wind, rumble
(filter 'lowpass
        (noise 'white 2.0)
        :cutoff 800
        :q 1.0)
```

```scheme
;; Highpass white noise → shimmer, breath
(filter 'highpass
        (noise 'white 2.0)
        :cutoff 4000
        :q 1.0)
```

```scheme
;; Bandpass + high Q → almost a tone, but noisy
(filter 'bandpass
        (noise 'white 1.5)
        :cutoff 1200
        :q 12.0)
```

*[needs: filter-verbs]*  
<!-- BUILD: filter-verbs — lowpass/highpass/bandpass with :cutoff :q params -->

The Q parameter controls resonance—how sharp the filter's peak is. Low Q is gentle. High Q rings.

---

## Enveloping Noise — Cymbal Crashes and Snare Hits

Noise with an envelope becomes a **hit**. A fast attack and slow decay: cymbal crash. A short burst: snare rattle. The ADSR from Chapter 5 shapes noise the same way it shapes tones.

```scheme
;; Cymbal crash — highpass noise with slow decay
(adsr (filter 'highpass
              (noise 'white 2.0)
              :cutoff 6000
              :q 1.5)
      :a 0.01
      :d 1.5
      :s 0.0
      :r 0.5)
```

```scheme
;; Snare rattle — bandpass noise, short envelope
(adsr (filter 'bandpass
              (noise 'white 0.3)
              :cutoff 2500
              :q 3.0)
      :a 0.005
      :d 0.15
      :s 0.0
      :r 0.1)
```

*[needs: adsr-verb]*  
<!-- BUILD: adsr-verb — ADSR envelope application -->

[VISUAL: Envelope diagram over a noise waveform — attack spike, decay slope, silence]

